can be authenticated

251
00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:31.650
in two different ways, right?

252
00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:34.530
We have agents that work
on behalf of the users,

253
00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:37.260
so essentially when a
user invokes that agent,

254
00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:41.130
that agent assumes that
user's credentials,

255
00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:44.340
passes that credential
as the off token

256
00:12:44.340 --> 00:12:47.910
and the appropriate permissions
of that user as well, right,

257
00:12:47.910 --> 00:12:51.870
when it comes to information
retrieval or task completion.

258
00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:53.250
But we also have another way

259
00:12:53.250 --> 00:12:55.770
that agents can maintain
their identity,

260
00:12:55.770 --> 00:13:00.120
and that's by leveraging their
own user identity, right,

261
00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:03.120
an agent user identity.

262
00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:07.740
What happens here is that agent
maintains their own identity

263
00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:10.740
and their own permissions,
and they pass that identity

264
00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:14.910
for authentication, and they're
able to function on their own

265
00:13:14.910 --> 00:13:20.400
without working on behalf of
a user, if that makes sense.

